Note:
SQL Parser - PostgreSQL-compatible AST construction

This file parses SQL tokens into an Abstract Syntax Tree (AST)
following PostgreSQL syntax and semantics.

Supported SQL Statements:
- SELECT: Full query support (WHERE, JOIN, GROUP BY, HAVING, ORDER BY, LIMIT, OFFSET)
- INSERT: INSERT INTO table (columns) VALUES (values)
- UPDATE: UPDATE table SET column = value WHERE condition
- DELETE: DELETE FROM table WHERE condition
- CREATE TABLE: CREATE TABLE name (columns and constraints)
- CREATE INDEX: CREATE INDEX name ON table (columns)
- DROP: DROP TABLE/INDEX name

AST Node Types:
- SQL_SELECT: SELECT query
- SQL_INSERT: INSERT statement
- SQL_UPDATE: UPDATE statement
- SQL_DELETE: DELETE statement
- SQL_CREATE_TABLE: CREATE TABLE statement
- SQL_CREATE_INDEX: CREATE INDEX statement
- SQL_DROP: DROP statement
- SQL_EXPRESSION: Expressions (binary ops, literals, identifiers, function calls)
- SQL_COLUMN_DEF: Column definition
- SQL_JOIN: JOIN clause
- SQL_WHERE: WHERE clause
- SQL_ORDER_BY: ORDER BY clause

Dependencies:
- sql_lexer.runa
- compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa
- compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa
- compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa
:End Note

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/sql/sql_lexer.runa" as Lexer
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List

Note: ============================================================================
Note: AST Node Types
Note: ============================================================================

Constant SQL_SELECT as Integer is 0
Constant SQL_INSERT as Integer is 1
Constant SQL_UPDATE as Integer is 2
Constant SQL_DELETE as Integer is 3
Constant SQL_CREATE_TABLE as Integer is 4
Constant SQL_CREATE_INDEX as Integer is 5
Constant SQL_DROP as Integer is 6
Constant SQL_EXPRESSION as Integer is 7
Constant SQL_COLUMN_DEF as Integer is 8
Constant SQL_JOIN as Integer is 9
Constant SQL_WHERE as Integer is 10
Constant SQL_ORDER_BY as Integer is 11
Constant SQL_GROUP_BY as Integer is 12
Constant SQL_IDENTIFIER as Integer is 13
Constant SQL_LITERAL as Integer is 14
Constant SQL_BINARY_OP as Integer is 15
Constant SQL_FUNCTION_CALL as Integer is 16
Constant SQL_COLUMN_REF as Integer is 17
Constant SQL_ALTER_TABLE as Integer is 18
Constant SQL_FROM as Integer is 19
Constant SQL_LIMIT as Integer is 20
Constant SQL_OFFSET as Integer is 21

Note: ============================================================================
Note: AST Node Structure
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Single AST node shape used for the entire SQL grammar (statements,
expressions, identifiers, literals). A flat children-list + metadata
slot is sufficient because SQL syntax never needs more than positional
ordering of children plus one auxiliary discriminator (operator type,
column-list flag, etc) per node.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
6 x i64 record (48 bytes). offsets: 0 = SQL_* node type, 8 = value
(string handle for identifiers/literals, op string for binary ops),
16 = children List handle, 24 = metadata (used as object type in
parse_drop, op token in binary ops), 32 = line, 40 = column. Children
list is allocated in create_sql_node so every node is fully initialized.
@End Implementation

Type called "SQLNode":
    type as Integer           Note: Node type constant
    value as Integer          Note: Value (for literals, identifiers)
    children as Integer       Note: List of child nodes
    metadata as Integer       Note: Additional data (operator type, column names, etc.)
    line as Integer           Note: Source line number
    column as Integer         Note: Source column number
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Parser Structure
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Parser state is tiny: a borrowed lexer handle, the cached current token
(populated by advance_token), and a sticky first-error pair. SQL
parsing is statement-scoped so there is no need to carry deeper
context (block scopes, type environments) at this layer.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
4 x i64 record (32 bytes). offsets: 0 = lexer handle (borrowed,
caller-owned), 8 = current token (also borrowed; tokens are owned by
the lexer's stream), 16 = error_message (owned heap copy, freed in
destroy_sql_parser), 24 = has_error bool. The current_token slot is
populated once at construction and bumped by advance_token after each
consumption.
@End Implementation

Type called "SQLParser":
    lexer as Integer          Note: SQL lexer
    current_token as Integer  Note: Current token
    error_message as Integer  Note: Error message (if any)
    has_error as Integer      Note: Boolean: 1 if error occurred
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Parser Creation and Destruction
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Wraps a borrowed lexer in a parser record and primes the
current_token slot by consuming the first token immediately. Priming
upfront means parse_* helpers can always consult current_token without
a special-case first call.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates 32 bytes via Layout (returns 0 on allocation failure). Sets
lexer at offset 0, current_token=0/has_error=0 placeholders, then
calls Lexer.next_token to populate current_token at offset 8.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_sql_parser" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create SQL parser

    Let parser_size be 32  Note: SQLParser: 4 fields × 8 bytes
    Let parser be proc allocate from Layout with parser_size

    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Initialize parser
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 0, lexer
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 8, 0   Note: current_token (will be set on first advance)
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 16, 0  Note: error_message = null
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 24, 0  Note: has_error = false

    Note: Get first token
    Let first_token be proc next_token from Lexer with lexer
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 8, first_token

    Return parser
End Process

@Reasoning:
The parser owns one heap allocation that survives across calls: the
error_message string copied in set_parser_error. Destruction must free
it before deallocating the parser record. The lexer is borrowed and
NOT owned, so it is left intact for the caller to destroy.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null guard returns 1. Reads error_message at offset 16; if non-zero,
Layout.deallocate releases the heap copy. Finally deallocates the
parser record. Lexer at offset 0 is intentionally not touched.
@End Implementation

Process called "destroy_sql_parser" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Destroy SQL parser

    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Free error message if exists
    Let error_message be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 16

    If error_message is not equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with error_message
    End If

    proc deallocate from Layout with parser

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: AST Node Creation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Single constructor for every node kind keeps allocation, children-list
setup, and field initialization centralized. Children must be created
together with the record so any later add_child can succeed without
re-checking liveness of the list slot.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates 48 bytes; on failure returns 0. Allocates an empty children
List via List.create_empty_list; on failure deallocates the partially
constructed node and returns 0 to keep the partial-allocation invariant
clean. Writes all six fields and returns the node handle.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_sql_node" takes node_type as Integer, value as Integer, metadata as Integer, line as Integer, column as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create SQL AST node

    Let node_size be 48  Note: SQLNode: 6 fields × 8 bytes
    Let node be proc allocate from Layout with node_size

    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Create children list
    Let children be proc create from List

    If children is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with node
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Initialize node
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 0, node_type
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 8, value
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 16, children
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 24, metadata
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 32, line
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 40, column

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Centralised child-attachment with null-safety on both arguments so
partial parse failures (which often return 0 for the child) can be
chained without explicit guards at the call site.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 0 if either parent or child is null. Otherwise reads the
parent's children list at offset 16 and appends the child via
List.append. Returns 1 on success.
@End Implementation

Process called "add_child" takes parent as Integer, child as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Add child node to parent

    If parent is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If child is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parent, 16
    proc append from List with children, child

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Token Access
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Accessor shared by every parse_* helper. Treating a null current_token
slot as TOKEN_EOF lets callers reach EOF naturally rather than crashing
on a null pointer if the lexer prematurely returned nothing.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads current_token at offset 8; if null returns Lexer.TOKEN_EOF
otherwise reads the i64 token-type field at offset 0 of the token
record.
@End Implementation

Process called "current_token_type" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get current token type

    Let token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8

    If token is equal to 0:
        Return TOKEN_EOF from Lexer
    End If

    Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0

    Return token_type
End Process

@Reasoning:
Single point of token-consumption: every parser helper that consumes a
token funnels through here so the lexer pull and current_token slot
update remain atomic.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the lexer handle at offset 0, asks Lexer.next_token for the next
token, and stores it at offset 8. Returns the new token handle so
callers can capture it without re-reading from offset 8.
@End Implementation

Process called "advance_token" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Advance to next token

    Let lexer be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 0
    Let new_token be proc next_token from Lexer with lexer

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 8, new_token

    Return new_token
End Process

@Reasoning:
Predicate for "is the current token X" used pervasively as the gate for
optional clauses (WHERE, GROUP BY, comma continuations). Distinct from
expect_token because it never raises an error — it just answers the
question.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls current_token_type and returns 1 if it equals expected_type, else
0. No side effects, no token consumption.
@End Implementation

Process called "check_token_type" takes parser as Integer, expected_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if current token matches expected type

    Let actual_type be proc current_token_type with parser

    If actual_type is equal to expected_type:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Mandatory-token gate: used at points where grammar requires a specific
keyword (FROM after SELECT columns, INTO after INSERT). Sets a parser
error rather than throwing so the caller can choose between error
recovery and bail-out.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Compares current_token_type with expected_type; on mismatch, calls
set_parser_error with the supplied error message and returns 0. On
match, returns 1 WITHOUT consuming the token — the caller invokes
advance_token explicitly so it controls when consumption happens.
@End Implementation

Process called "expect_token" takes parser as Integer, expected_type as Integer, error_msg as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Expect specific token type, set error if not found

    Let actual_type be proc current_token_type with parser

    If actual_type is not equal to expected_type:
        proc set_parser_error with parser, error_msg
        Return 0
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Error Handling
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Last-error wins behaviour because the most informative diagnostic
about a failed parse is typically the one closest to the failure
point. Copying the message into a parser-owned buffer decouples the
error string's lifetime from the caller's transient diagnostic string.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Frees any previously stored error_message (offset 16) before
overwriting. Allocates msg_length+1 bytes, memcpys the message, writes
a null terminator, and stores the new handle at offset 16. Sets
has_error (offset 24) to 1 so callers can short-circuit. Returns 1.
@End Implementation

Process called "set_parser_error" takes parser as Integer, message as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Set parser error message

    Let error_message be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 16

    Note: Free previous error if exists
    If error_message is not equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with error_message
    End If

    Note: Copy error message
    Let msg_length be proc string_length from StringCore with message
    Let new_error be proc allocate from Layout with msg_length plus 1

    If new_error is not equal to 0:
        proc memory_copy from Layout with new_error, message, msg_length
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with new_error, msg_length, 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 16, new_error
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 24, 1  Note: has_error = true

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Expression Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The bottom of the SQL precedence hierarchy. Handles every form that
can stand on its own: integer/float/string literals, identifiers
(possibly qualified), parenthesised expressions, function calls,
NULL/TRUE/FALSE keywords, and the unary `*` (SELECT *). Above this,
parse_comparison_expression/parse_and_expression/parse_expression
layer the relational and logical operators.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the current token's type, line, and column. Sequentially checks
TOKEN_INTEGER/FLOAT/STRING (each emits a literal node), TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
(emits identifier node, with lookahead for `.` -> qualified name and
`(` -> function call), TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN (recurses into parse_expression
and consumes the closing paren), TOKEN_NULL/TRUE/FALSE/ASTERISK
(keyword/wildcard nodes). Returns 0 if nothing matches, signalling
"not an expression here" to the caller.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_primary_expression" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse primary expression (literal, identifier, function call, parenthesized expression)

    Let token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
    Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 32

    Note: Check for literals
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_INTEGER from Lexer:
        Let lexeme be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
        Let length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 16

        Let value be proc allocate from Layout with length plus 1
        proc memory_copy from Layout with value, lexeme, length
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with value, length, 0

        Let node be proc create_sql_node with SQL_LITERAL, value, TOKEN_INTEGER from Lexer, line, column
        proc advance_token with parser
        Return node
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_FLOAT from Lexer:
        Set lexeme to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
        Set length to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 16

        Set value to proc allocate from Layout with length plus 1
        proc memory_copy from Layout with value, lexeme, length
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with value, length, 0

        Set node to proc create_sql_node with SQL_LITERAL, value, TOKEN_FLOAT from Lexer, line, column
        proc advance_token with parser
        Return node
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_STRING from Lexer:
        Set lexeme to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
        Set length to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 16

        Note: Copy the string content, collapsing each doubled single quote
        Note: ('') in SQL escaping back to a single quote so the stored value
        Note: is the true content. The emitter re-doubles quotes on output.
        Set value to proc allocate from Layout with length plus 1
        Let src_index be 0
        Let dst_index be 0
        While src_index is less than length:
            Let ch be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with lexeme, src_index
            If ch is equal to 39:
                Let nxt_index be src_index plus 1
                If nxt_index is less than length:
                    Let nxt be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with lexeme, nxt_index
                    If nxt is equal to 39:
                        Set src_index to src_index plus 1
                    End If
                End If
            End If
            proc memory_set_byte from Layout with value, dst_index, ch
            Set dst_index to dst_index plus 1
            Set src_index to src_index plus 1
        End While
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with value, dst_index, 0

        Set node to proc create_sql_node with SQL_LITERAL, value, TOKEN_STRING from Lexer, line, column
        proc advance_token with parser
        Return node
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_TRUE from Lexer:
        Set value to "TRUE"
        Set node to proc create_sql_node with SQL_LITERAL, value, TOKEN_TRUE from Lexer, line, column
        proc advance_token with parser
        Return node
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_FALSE from Lexer:
        Set value to "FALSE"
        Set node to proc create_sql_node with SQL_LITERAL, value, TOKEN_FALSE from Lexer, line, column
        proc advance_token with parser
        Return node
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_NULL from Lexer:
        Set value to "NULL"
        Set node to proc create_sql_node with SQL_LITERAL, value, TOKEN_NULL from Lexer, line, column
        proc advance_token with parser
        Return node
    End If

    Note: Check for identifier or function call
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer:
        Set lexeme to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
        Set length to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 16

        Let identifier be proc allocate from Layout with length plus 1
        proc memory_copy from Layout with identifier, lexeme, length
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with identifier, length, 0

        proc advance_token with parser

        Note: Check for function call (identifier followed by '(')
        Let is_left_paren be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN from Lexer

        If is_left_paren is equal to 1:
            Let func_node be proc create_sql_node with SQL_FUNCTION_CALL, identifier, 0, line, column

            proc advance_token with parser  Note: Consume '('

            Note: Parse function arguments
            Let is_right_paren be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN from Lexer

            If is_right_paren is equal to 0:
                While 1 is equal to 1:
                    Let arg be proc parse_expression with parser

                    If arg is not equal to 0:
                        proc add_child with func_node, arg
                    End If

                    Let is_comma be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_COMMA from Lexer

                    If is_comma is equal to 1:
                        proc advance_token with parser  Note: Consume ','
                    Otherwise:
                        Break
                    End If
                End While
            End If

            proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN from Lexer, "Expected ')' after function arguments"
            proc advance_token with parser  Note: Consume ')'

            Return func_node
        Otherwise:
            Note: Check for column reference (table.column)
            Let is_dot be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_DOT from Lexer

            If is_dot is equal to 1:
                proc advance_token with parser  Note: Consume '.'

                Let col_token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
                Let col_lexeme be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with col_token, 8
                Let col_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with col_token, 16

                Let column_name be proc allocate from Layout with col_length plus 1
                proc memory_copy from Layout with column_name, col_lexeme, col_length
                proc memory_set_byte from Layout with column_name, col_length, 0

                proc advance_token with parser

                Note: Create column reference node with table.column
                Let col_ref be proc create_sql_node with SQL_COLUMN_REF, column_name, 0, line, column
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with col_ref, 24, identifier  Note: Store table name in metadata

                Return col_ref
            Otherwise:
                Note: Simple identifier
                Set node to proc create_sql_node with SQL_IDENTIFIER, identifier, 0, line, column
                Return node
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Note: Check for star (SELECT *)
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_STAR from Lexer:
        Set value to "*"
        Set node to proc create_sql_node with SQL_IDENTIFIER, value, 0, line, column
        proc advance_token with parser
        Return node
    End If

    Note: Check for parenthesized expression
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser  Note: Consume '('

        Let expr be proc parse_expression with parser

        proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN from Lexer, "Expected ')' after expression"
        proc advance_token with parser  Note: Consume ')'

        Return expr
    End If

    Return 0  Note: Not a valid primary expression
End Process

@Reasoning:
Implements SQL's relational layer: precedence between primary and AND.
Returns the left operand untouched when no comparison operator is
present, so this function acts as a transparent pass-through for
non-comparison expressions.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Parses a primary expression as the left operand; null-checks. Looks at
the next token; for each of TOKEN_EQUAL, TOKEN_NOT_EQUAL,
TOKEN_LESS_THAN, TOKEN_GREATER_THAN, TOKEN_LESS_EQUAL,
TOKEN_GREATER_EQUAL: captures token line/column, consumes the operator,
parses the right operand, and builds a SQL_BINARY_OP node with the op
spelling (=, <>, <, >, <=, >=) as value and the lexer token id as
metadata. If the right operand fails, returns the left unchanged to
keep partial parse usable.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_comparison_expression" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse comparison expression (=, <>, <, >, <=, >=)

    Let left be proc parse_primary_expression with parser

    If left is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let token_type be proc current_token_type with parser

    Note: Check for comparison operators
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_EQUAL from Lexer:
        Let token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
        Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 24
        Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 32

        proc advance_token with parser

        Let right be proc parse_primary_expression with parser

        If right is equal to 0:
            Return left
        End If

        Let op_value be "="
        Let binary_node be proc create_sql_node with SQL_BINARY_OP, op_value, TOKEN_EQUAL from Lexer, line, column
        proc add_child with binary_node, left
        proc add_child with binary_node, right

        Return binary_node
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_NOT_EQUAL from Lexer:
        Set token to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
        Set line to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 24
        Set column to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 32

        proc advance_token with parser

        Set right to proc parse_primary_expression with parser

        If right is equal to 0:
            Return left
        End If

        Set op_value to "<>"
        Set binary_node to proc create_sql_node with SQL_BINARY_OP, op_value, TOKEN_NOT_EQUAL from Lexer, line, column
        proc add_child with binary_node, left
        proc add_child with binary_node, right

        Return binary_node
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_LESS_THAN from Lexer:
        Set token to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
        Set line to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 24
        Set column to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 32

        proc advance_token with parser

        Set right to proc parse_primary_expression with parser

        If right is equal to 0:
            Return left
        End If

        Set op_value to "<"
        Set binary_node to proc create_sql_node with SQL_BINARY_OP, op_value, TOKEN_LESS_THAN from Lexer, line, column
        proc add_child with binary_node, left
        proc add_child with binary_node, right

        Return binary_node
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_GREATER_THAN from Lexer:
        Set token to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
        Set line to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 24
        Set column to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 32

        proc advance_token with parser

        Set right to proc parse_primary_expression with parser

        If right is equal to 0:
            Return left
        End If

        Set op_value to ">"
        Set binary_node to proc create_sql_node with SQL_BINARY_OP, op_value, TOKEN_GREATER_THAN from Lexer, line, column
        proc add_child with binary_node, left
        proc add_child with binary_node, right

        Return binary_node
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_LESS_EQUAL from Lexer:
        Set token to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
        Set line to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 24
        Set column to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 32

        proc advance_token with parser

        Set right to proc parse_primary_expression with parser

        If right is equal to 0:
            Return left
        End If

        Set op_value to "<="
        Set binary_node to proc create_sql_node with SQL_BINARY_OP, op_value, TOKEN_LESS_EQUAL from Lexer, line, column
        proc add_child with binary_node, left
        proc add_child with binary_node, right

        Return binary_node
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_GREATER_EQUAL from Lexer:
        Set token to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
        Set line to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 24
        Set column to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 32

        proc advance_token with parser

        Set right to proc parse_primary_expression with parser

        If right is equal to 0:
            Return left
        End If

        Set op_value to ">="
        Set binary_node to proc create_sql_node with SQL_BINARY_OP, op_value, TOKEN_GREATER_EQUAL from Lexer, line, column
        proc add_child with binary_node, left
        proc add_child with binary_node, right

        Return binary_node
    End If

    Return left
End Process

@Reasoning:
SQL precedence: AND binds tighter than OR. This level chains zero or
more `AND comparison` to the left operand and builds a left-associative
tree of binary ops, matching standard SQL evaluation order.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Parses an initial comparison expression; null check. Loop: stop when
the current token is not TOKEN_AND. Otherwise capture position,
consume AND, parse a comparison as right operand (break on failure),
build a SQL_BINARY_OP node with value="AND" and metadata=TOKEN_AND,
and rebind left to the new node for left-associativity.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_and_expression" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse AND expression

    Let left be proc parse_comparison_expression with parser

    If left is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let is_and be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_AND from Lexer

        If is_and is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        Let token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
        Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 24
        Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 32

        proc advance_token with parser

        Let right be proc parse_comparison_expression with parser

        If right is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        Let op_value be "AND"
        Let and_node be proc create_sql_node with SQL_BINARY_OP, op_value, TOKEN_AND from Lexer, line, column
        proc add_child with and_node, left
        proc add_child with and_node, right

        Set left to and_node
    End While

    Return left
End Process

@Reasoning:
Top of the expression precedence ladder for SQL: OR is the lowest-
precedence boolean connective. Every statement-level expression
(WHERE clause, ON, HAVING, VALUES item) enters the expression grammar
through here.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Parses an AND expression as left operand; null check. Loop: stop when
current token is not TOKEN_OR. Otherwise capture position, consume OR,
parse next AND expression as right (break on failure), build a
SQL_BINARY_OP node with value="OR" and metadata=TOKEN_OR, rebind left
to the OR node. Left-associative — mirrors the AND layer.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_expression" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse OR expression (top level)

    Let left be proc parse_and_expression with parser

    If left is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let is_or be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_OR from Lexer

        If is_or is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        Let token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
        Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 24
        Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 32

        proc advance_token with parser

        Let right be proc parse_and_expression with parser

        If right is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        Let op_value be "OR"
        Let or_node be proc create_sql_node with SQL_BINARY_OP, op_value, TOKEN_OR from Lexer, line, column
        proc add_child with or_node, left
        proc add_child with or_node, right

        Set left to or_node
    End While

    Return left
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SELECT Statement Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
SELECT is the most structurally complex SQL statement: SELECT list,
FROM tables/joins, optional WHERE / GROUP BY / HAVING / ORDER BY /
LIMIT clauses. Building each clause as a sub-node with a dedicated
SQL_* type lets downstream passes navigate the AST without re-parsing
or guessing clause boundaries.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Captures position from SELECT token, builds a SQL_SELECT parent. Then
sequentially: consumes SELECT keyword, parses comma-separated column
list (each item via parse_expression, supports `*` wildcard), expects
FROM, parses table list (comma-separated identifiers possibly with
join syntax), then optionally consumes and parses WHERE/GROUP BY/
HAVING/ORDER BY/LIMIT in canonical order. Each optional clause is
wrapped in its own SQL_* node attached as a child of the SELECT.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_select" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse SELECT statement

    Let token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 32

    Let select_node be proc create_sql_node with SQL_SELECT, 0, 0, line, column

    proc advance_token with parser  Note: Consume SELECT

    Note: Check for DISTINCT
    Let is_distinct be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_DISTINCT from Lexer

    If is_distinct is equal to 1:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with select_node, 24, 1  Note: Set DISTINCT flag in metadata
        proc advance_token with parser
    End If

    Note: Parse SELECT list (columns)
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let col_expr be proc parse_primary_expression with parser

        If col_expr is not equal to 0:
            proc add_child with select_node, col_expr
        End If

        Let is_comma be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_COMMA from Lexer

        If is_comma is equal to 1:
            proc advance_token with parser  Note: Consume ','
        Otherwise:
            Break
        End If
    End While

    Note: Parse FROM clause (optional for some queries)
    Let is_from be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_FROM from Lexer

    If is_from is equal to 1:
        proc advance_token with parser  Note: Consume FROM

        Let table_expr be proc parse_primary_expression with parser

        If table_expr is not equal to 0:
            Note: Wrap the FROM table in a SQL_FROM marker so the lowerer can
            Note: distinguish it from SELECT-list columns (both are identifiers).
            Let from_node be proc create_sql_node with SQL_FROM, 0, 0, line, column
            proc add_child with from_node, table_expr
            proc add_child with select_node, from_node
        End If

        Note: Parse JOIN clauses (optional)
        While 1 is equal to 1:
            Let is_join be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_JOIN from Lexer
            Let is_inner be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_INNER from Lexer
            Let is_left be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_LEFT from Lexer
            Let is_right be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_RIGHT from Lexer

            If is_join is equal to 0:
                If is_inner is equal to 0:
                    If is_left is equal to 0:
                        If is_right is equal to 0:
                            Break
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End If

            Note: Determine JOIN type
            Let join_type be 0  Note: 0 = INNER, 1 = LEFT, 2 = RIGHT

            If is_inner is equal to 1:
                proc advance_token with parser
                Set join_type to 0
            Otherwise If is_left is equal to 1:
                proc advance_token with parser
                Set join_type to 1
            Otherwise If is_right is equal to 1:
                proc advance_token with parser
                Set join_type to 2
            End If

            Let join_token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
            Let join_line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with join_token, 24
            Let join_column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with join_token, 32

            proc advance_token with parser  Note: Consume JOIN

            Let join_node be proc create_sql_node with SQL_JOIN, 0, join_type, join_line, join_column

            Note: Parse joined table
            Let joined_table be proc parse_primary_expression with parser

            If joined_table is not equal to 0:
                proc add_child with join_node, joined_table
            End If

            Note: Parse ON clause
            Let is_on be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_ON from Lexer

            If is_on is equal to 1:
                proc advance_token with parser  Note: Consume ON

                Let on_condition be proc parse_expression with parser

                If on_condition is not equal to 0:
                    proc add_child with join_node, on_condition
                End If
            End If

            proc add_child with select_node, join_node
        End While
    End If

    Note: Parse WHERE clause (optional)
    Let is_where be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_WHERE from Lexer

    If is_where is equal to 1:
        proc advance_token with parser  Note: Consume WHERE

        Let where_condition be proc parse_expression with parser

        If where_condition is not equal to 0:
            Let where_token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
            Let where_line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with where_token, 24
            Let where_column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with where_token, 32

            Let where_node be proc create_sql_node with SQL_WHERE, 0, 0, where_line, where_column
            proc add_child with where_node, where_condition
            proc add_child with select_node, where_node
        End If
    End If

    Note: Parse GROUP BY clause (optional)
    Let is_group be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_GROUP from Lexer

    If is_group is equal to 1:
        proc advance_token with parser  Note: Consume GROUP

        proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_BY from Lexer, "Expected BY after GROUP"
        proc advance_token with parser  Note: Consume BY

        Let group_token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
        Let group_line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with group_token, 24
        Let group_column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with group_token, 32

        Let group_node be proc create_sql_node with SQL_GROUP_BY, 0, 0, group_line, group_column

        While 1 is equal to 1:
            Let group_expr be proc parse_primary_expression with parser

            If group_expr is not equal to 0:
                proc add_child with group_node, group_expr
            End If

            Set is_comma to proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_COMMA from Lexer

            If is_comma is equal to 1:
                proc advance_token with parser
            Otherwise:
                Break
            End If
        End While

        proc add_child with select_node, group_node
    End If

    Note: Parse ORDER BY clause (optional)
    Let is_order be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_ORDER from Lexer

    If is_order is equal to 1:
        proc advance_token with parser  Note: Consume ORDER

        proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_BY from Lexer, "Expected BY after ORDER"
        proc advance_token with parser  Note: Consume BY

        Let order_token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
        Let order_line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with order_token, 24
        Let order_column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with order_token, 32

        Let order_node be proc create_sql_node with SQL_ORDER_BY, 0, 0, order_line, order_column

        While 1 is equal to 1:
            Let order_expr be proc parse_primary_expression with parser

            If order_expr is not equal to 0:
                proc add_child with order_node, order_expr
            End If

            Set is_comma to proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_COMMA from Lexer

            If is_comma is equal to 1:
                proc advance_token with parser
            Otherwise:
                Break
            End If
        End While

        proc add_child with select_node, order_node
    End If

    Note: Parse LIMIT clause (optional)
    Let is_limit be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_LIMIT from Lexer

    If is_limit is equal to 1:
        proc advance_token with parser  Note: Consume LIMIT

        Let limit_expr be proc parse_primary_expression with parser

        If limit_expr is not equal to 0:
            Let limit_node be proc create_sql_node with SQL_LIMIT, 0, 0, line, column
            proc add_child with limit_node, limit_expr
            proc add_child with select_node, limit_node
        End If
    End If

    Note: Parse OFFSET clause (optional)
    Let is_offset be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_OFFSET from Lexer

    If is_offset is equal to 1:
        proc advance_token with parser  Note: Consume OFFSET

        Let offset_expr be proc parse_primary_expression with parser

        If offset_expr is not equal to 0:
            Let offset_node be proc create_sql_node with SQL_OFFSET, 0, 0, line, column
            proc add_child with offset_node, offset_expr
            proc add_child with select_node, offset_node
        End If
    End If

    Return select_node
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: INSERT Statement Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
INSERT INTO table (col, col, ...) VALUES (expr, expr, ...). Both the
column list and the values list are optional in syntax form, but if
columns are listed the values must match arity. AST tree keeps table
as first child, then column-name children (if any), then value
expression children; the count match is checked semantically later.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Builds a SQL_INSERT parent at the INSERT token's position. Consumes
INSERT, expects/consumes INTO, parses table name as a primary
expression and attaches it. Optional `(col, col, ...)` list: enters
when current token is `(`, parses comma-separated primary expressions
until `)`. Mandatory VALUES keyword and `(`. Loop parses comma-
separated value expressions via parse_expression. Closes with `)`.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_insert" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse INSERT statement

    Let token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 32

    Let insert_node be proc create_sql_node with SQL_INSERT, 0, 0, line, column

    proc advance_token with parser  Note: Consume INSERT

    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_INTO from Lexer, "Expected INTO after INSERT"
    proc advance_token with parser  Note: Consume INTO

    Note: Parse table name
    Let table_name be proc parse_table_name with parser

    If table_name is not equal to 0:
        proc add_child with insert_node, table_name
    End If

    Note: Parse column list (optional)
    Let is_left_paren be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN from Lexer

    If is_left_paren is equal to 1:
        proc advance_token with parser  Note: Consume '('

        While 1 is equal to 1:
            Let col_name be proc parse_primary_expression with parser

            If col_name is not equal to 0:
                proc add_child with insert_node, col_name
            End If

            Let is_comma be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_COMMA from Lexer

            If is_comma is equal to 1:
                proc advance_token with parser
            Otherwise:
                Break
            End If
        End While

        proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN from Lexer, "Expected ')' after column list"
        proc advance_token with parser  Note: Consume ')'
    End If

    Note: Parse VALUES clause
    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_VALUES from Lexer, "Expected VALUES"
    proc advance_token with parser  Note: Consume VALUES

    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN from Lexer, "Expected '(' after VALUES"
    proc advance_token with parser  Note: Consume '('

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let value_expr be proc parse_expression with parser

        If value_expr is not equal to 0:
            proc add_child with insert_node, value_expr
        End If

        Set is_comma to proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_COMMA from Lexer

        If is_comma is equal to 1:
            proc advance_token with parser
        Otherwise:
            Break
        End If
    End While

    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN from Lexer, "Expected ')' after VALUES"
    proc advance_token with parser  Note: Consume ')'

    Return insert_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
UPDATE has the same overall shape as INSERT (table + column actions +
optional WHERE) but each column action is a `col = expr` pair rather
than a positional value. Each assignment is modelled as a SQL_BINARY_OP
node so later passes can reuse the binary-op visitor.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Builds a SQL_UPDATE parent. Consumes UPDATE, parses table name primary
expression and attaches. Expects/consumes SET. Loop: parse column name
(primary expression), expect/consume `=`, parse value expression,
build a SQL_BINARY_OP assignment node with col_name + value_expr as
children, attach to update_node. Comma continues the loop; anything
else breaks. Optional WHERE branch wraps the parsed condition in a
SQL_WHERE node and attaches it.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_update" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse UPDATE statement
    Note: Format: UPDATE table SET column = value, ... WHERE condition

    Let token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 32

    Let update_node be proc create_sql_node with SQL_UPDATE, 0, 0, line, column

    proc advance_token with parser  Note: Consume UPDATE

    Note: Parse table name
    Let table_name be proc parse_table_name with parser

    If table_name is not equal to 0:
        proc add_child with update_node, table_name
    End If

    Note: Parse SET clause
    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_SET from Lexer, "Expected SET after table name"
    proc advance_token with parser  Note: Consume SET

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Note: Parse column = value assignment
        Let col_name be proc parse_primary_expression with parser

        proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_EQUAL from Lexer, "Expected '=' after column name"
        proc advance_token with parser  Note: Consume '='

        Let value_expr be proc parse_expression with parser

        Note: Create assignment pair node
        Let assignment be proc create_sql_node with SQL_BINARY_OP, 0, 0, line, column
        proc add_child with assignment, col_name
        proc add_child with assignment, value_expr
        proc add_child with update_node, assignment

        Let is_comma be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_COMMA from Lexer

        If is_comma is equal to 1:
            proc advance_token with parser
        Otherwise:
            Break
        End If
    End While

    Note: Parse optional WHERE clause
    Let is_where be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_WHERE from Lexer

    If is_where is equal to 1:
        proc advance_token with parser  Note: Consume WHERE

        Let where_expr be proc parse_expression with parser

        If where_expr is not equal to 0:
            Let where_node be proc create_sql_node with SQL_WHERE, 0, 0, line, column
            proc add_child with where_node, where_expr
            proc add_child with update_node, where_node
        End If
    End If

    Return update_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
DELETE is the simplest mutation: a table and an optional WHERE. We
model the WHERE the same way as in UPDATE/SELECT — wrapped in a
SQL_WHERE node — so the same downstream code can handle WHERE
predicates uniformly.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Builds a SQL_DELETE parent at the DELETE position. Consumes DELETE,
expects/consumes FROM, parses table name primary expression and
attaches. If current token is WHERE, consumes it, parses the predicate
expression, wraps it in a SQL_WHERE node, and attaches.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_delete" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse DELETE statement
    Note: Format: DELETE FROM table WHERE condition

    Let token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 32

    Let delete_node be proc create_sql_node with SQL_DELETE, 0, 0, line, column

    proc advance_token with parser  Note: Consume DELETE

    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_FROM from Lexer, "Expected FROM after DELETE"
    proc advance_token with parser  Note: Consume FROM

    Note: Parse table name
    Let table_name be proc parse_table_name with parser

    If table_name is not equal to 0:
        proc add_child with delete_node, table_name
    End If

    Note: Parse optional WHERE clause
    Let is_where be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_WHERE from Lexer

    If is_where is equal to 1:
        proc advance_token with parser  Note: Consume WHERE

        Let where_expr be proc parse_expression with parser

        If where_expr is not equal to 0:
            Let where_node be proc create_sql_node with SQL_WHERE, 0, 0, line, column
            proc add_child with where_node, where_expr
            proc add_child with delete_node, where_node
        End If
    End If

    Return delete_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
CREATE TABLE produces a SQL_COLUMN_DEF for each column with the column
name, type, and a flat list of constraint nodes. Constraints (NOT NULL,
PRIMARY KEY, UNIQUE, DEFAULT expr) are modelled as SQL_IDENTIFIER nodes
carrying the constraint name in their value field so the downstream
translator can dispatch on the string rather than a separate
constraint-kind enum.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes CREATE TABLE, parses table-name primary expression. Inside
`(...)`: parses column definitions until `)`. Each column def: name +
type via two primary-expression parses; then a constraint loop that
matches NOT (followed by NULL), PRIMARY (followed by KEY), UNIQUE,
DEFAULT (followed by value expression). Each constraint becomes a
SQL_IDENTIFIER attached as a child of the SQL_COLUMN_DEF; DEFAULT's
value is attached as a grandchild. Outer loop continues on comma,
breaks otherwise.
@End Implementation

@Reasoning:
Column types in SQL are keyword tokens (INTEGER, VARCHAR, TEXT, ...) or
plain identifiers for user-defined / unrecognised type names. The general
parse_primary_expression only accepts identifiers and literals, so a
dedicated type reader is required to capture data-type keywords plus an
optional size/precision parenthesised argument list (e.g. VARCHAR(255),
NUMERIC(10, 2)). The result is a SQL_IDENTIFIER node carrying the full
type spelling as its value so the downstream lowerer/emitter can render
the original type verbatim.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Captures the current token's lexeme, length, line, column. Builds a
null-terminated copy of the lexeme as the type name and consumes the
token regardless of its keyword/identifier kind. If a '(' immediately
follows, consumes the size/precision argument list verbatim into the
type spelling (digits, commas, identifiers) until the matching ')',
appending '(...)' to the type name so VARCHAR(255) survives as one type
token. Returns a SQL_IDENTIFIER node.
@End Implementation

@Reasoning:
Table and object names must be parsed as bare identifiers, never as
function calls. parse_primary_expression greedily treats `name (` as a
function call, which is catastrophic for "CREATE TABLE accounts (cols...)"
and "INSERT INTO accounts (cols...)" where the parenthesis introduces the
column/values list, not call arguments. This helper consumes exactly one
identifier (optionally dotted: schema.table) and stops, leaving any
following '(' for the caller's column/value-list parser.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Requires the current token to be an identifier; on mismatch returns 0.
Copies the identifier lexeme into a heap buffer and consumes it. If a '.'
immediately follows, consumes it and the next identifier, building a
SQL_COLUMN_REF node (schema.table); otherwise returns a SQL_IDENTIFIER
node. Never consumes a following '('.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_table_name" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse a table/object name as a bare (optionally dotted) identifier

    Let token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8

    If token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0

    If token_type is not equal to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let lexeme be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
    Let length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 16
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 32

    Let name be proc allocate from Layout with length plus 1
    proc memory_copy from Layout with name, lexeme, length
    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with name, length, 0

    proc advance_token with parser

    Note: Optional schema.table qualification
    Let is_dot be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_DOT from Lexer

    If is_dot is equal to 1:
        proc advance_token with parser  Note: Consume '.'

        Let part_token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
        Let part_lexeme be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with part_token, 8
        Let part_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with part_token, 16

        Let part_name be proc allocate from Layout with part_length plus 1
        proc memory_copy from Layout with part_name, part_lexeme, part_length
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with part_name, part_length, 0

        proc advance_token with parser

        Let col_ref be proc create_sql_node with SQL_COLUMN_REF, part_name, 0, line, column
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with col_ref, 24, name  Note: schema/table in metadata

        Return col_ref
    End If

    Let name_node be proc create_sql_node with SQL_IDENTIFIER, name, 0, line, column

    Return name_node
End Process

Process called "parse_column_type" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse a column data type (keyword type or identifier) with optional (size)

    Let token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8

    If token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let lexeme be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
    Let length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 16
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 32

    If lexeme is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Copy the base type name
    Let type_name be proc allocate from Layout with length plus 1
    proc memory_copy from Layout with type_name, lexeme, length
    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with type_name, length, 0

    proc advance_token with parser  Note: Consume the type token

    Note: Optional (size) or (precision, scale)
    Let is_left_paren be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN from Lexer

    If is_left_paren is equal to 1:
        Note: Span the full "TYPE(args)" run from the source so the spelling is
        Note: preserved exactly. The base type token starts at start_lexeme; the
        Note: end is the byte one past the closing ')' lexeme.
        Let start_lexeme be lexeme
        proc advance_token with parser  Note: Consume '('

        Let close_end be 0

        While 1 is equal to 1:
            Let is_rp be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN from Lexer

            If is_rp is equal to 1:
                Let rp_token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
                Let rp_lexeme be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with rp_token, 8
                Let rp_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with rp_token, 16
                Set close_end to rp_lexeme plus rp_length
                proc advance_token with parser  Note: Consume ')'
                Break
            End If

            Let cur be proc current_token_type with parser

            If cur is equal to TOKEN_EOF from Lexer:
                Break
            End If

            proc advance_token with parser
        End While

        Note: Recompute the spelling to span from the type token start through ')'.
        If close_end is greater than start_lexeme:
            Let full_length be close_end minus start_lexeme
            Let spelled be proc allocate from Layout with full_length plus 1
            proc memory_copy from Layout with spelled, start_lexeme, full_length
            proc memory_set_byte from Layout with spelled, full_length, 0
            proc deallocate from Layout with type_name
            Set type_name to spelled
        End If
    End If

    Let type_node be proc create_sql_node with SQL_IDENTIFIER, type_name, 0, line, column

    Return type_node
End Process

Process called "parse_create_table" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse CREATE TABLE statement
    Note: Format: CREATE TABLE name (column_name type constraints, ...)

    Let token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 32

    Let create_node be proc create_sql_node with SQL_CREATE_TABLE, 0, 0, line, column

    proc advance_token with parser  Note: Consume CREATE

    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_TABLE from Lexer, "Expected TABLE after CREATE"
    proc advance_token with parser  Note: Consume TABLE

    Note: Parse table name
    Let table_name be proc parse_table_name with parser

    If table_name is not equal to 0:
        proc add_child with create_node, table_name
    End If

    Note: Parse column definitions
    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN from Lexer, "Expected '(' after table name"
    proc advance_token with parser  Note: Consume '('

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Note: Parse column definition (name + type + constraints)
        Let col_name be proc parse_primary_expression with parser
        Let col_type be proc parse_column_type with parser

        Let col_def be proc create_sql_node with SQL_COLUMN_DEF, 0, 0, line, column
        proc add_child with col_def, col_name
        proc add_child with col_def, col_type

        Note: Parse optional constraints (NOT NULL, PRIMARY KEY, etc.)
        While 1 is equal to 1:
            Let is_not be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_NOT from Lexer
            Let is_null be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_NULL from Lexer
            Let is_primary be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_PRIMARY from Lexer
            Let is_unique be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_UNIQUE from Lexer
            Let is_default be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_DEFAULT from Lexer

            If is_not is equal to 1:
                proc advance_token with parser
                proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_NULL from Lexer, "Expected NULL after NOT"
                proc advance_token with parser
                Let constraint_node be proc create_sql_node with SQL_IDENTIFIER, 0, 0, line, column
                Let constraint_name be "NOT NULL"
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with constraint_node, 8, constraint_name
                proc add_child with col_def, constraint_node
            Otherwise If is_primary is equal to 1:
                proc advance_token with parser
                proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_KEY from Lexer, "Expected KEY after PRIMARY"
                proc advance_token with parser
                Set constraint_node to proc create_sql_node with SQL_IDENTIFIER, 0, 0, line, column
                Set constraint_name to "PRIMARY KEY"
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with constraint_node, 8, constraint_name
                proc add_child with col_def, constraint_node
            Otherwise If is_unique is equal to 1:
                proc advance_token with parser
                Set constraint_node to proc create_sql_node with SQL_IDENTIFIER, 0, 0, line, column
                Set constraint_name to "UNIQUE"
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with constraint_node, 8, constraint_name
                proc add_child with col_def, constraint_node
            Otherwise If is_default is equal to 1:
                proc advance_token with parser
                Let default_value be proc parse_primary_expression with parser
                Set constraint_node to proc create_sql_node with SQL_IDENTIFIER, 0, 0, line, column
                Set constraint_name to "DEFAULT"
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with constraint_node, 8, constraint_name
                proc add_child with constraint_node, default_value
                proc add_child with col_def, constraint_node
            Otherwise:
                Break
            End If
        End While

        proc add_child with create_node, col_def

        Let is_comma be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_COMMA from Lexer

        If is_comma is equal to 1:
            proc advance_token with parser
        Otherwise:
            Break
        End If
    End While

    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN from Lexer, "Expected ')' after column definitions"
    proc advance_token with parser  Note: Consume ')'

    Return create_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
ALTER TABLE in SQL has several variant action shapes. The bootstrap
implementation supports ADD COLUMN and DROP COLUMN — the most common
forms. The action is wrapped in a SQL_IDENTIFIER named "ADD" / "DROP"
to keep dispatch downstream symmetrical with column constraints.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes ALTER TABLE then parses the table-name primary expression.
Looks at the next token: ADD branch consumes ADD plus optional COLUMN
keyword, parses col_name + col_type into a SQL_COLUMN_DEF, wraps in a
SQL_IDENTIFIER("ADD") action node, attaches under alter_node. DROP
branch consumes DROP plus optional COLUMN, parses col_name only,
wraps in SQL_IDENTIFIER("DROP") action node, attaches. Anything else
falls through leaving alter_node without an action child.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_alter_table" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse ALTER TABLE statement
    Note: Format: ALTER TABLE name ADD/DROP/ALTER COLUMN ...

    Let token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 32

    Let alter_node be proc create_sql_node with SQL_ALTER_TABLE, 0, 0, line, column

    proc advance_token with parser  Note: Consume ALTER

    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_TABLE from Lexer, "Expected TABLE after ALTER"
    proc advance_token with parser  Note: Consume TABLE

    Note: Parse table name
    Let table_name be proc parse_table_name with parser

    If table_name is not equal to 0:
        proc add_child with alter_node, table_name
    End If

    Note: Parse ALTER action (ADD, DROP, ALTER)
    Let is_add be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_ADD from Lexer
    Let is_drop be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_DROP from Lexer

    If is_add is equal to 1:
        proc advance_token with parser

        Note: Expect COLUMN keyword (optional in some SQL dialects)
        Let is_column be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_COLUMN from Lexer
        If is_column is equal to 1:
            proc advance_token with parser
        End If

        Note: Parse column definition
        Let col_name be proc parse_primary_expression with parser
        Let col_type be proc parse_column_type with parser

        Let col_def be proc create_sql_node with SQL_COLUMN_DEF, 0, 0, line, column
        proc add_child with col_def, col_name
        proc add_child with col_def, col_type

        Let action_node be proc create_sql_node with SQL_IDENTIFIER, 0, 0, line, column
        Let action_name be "ADD"
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with action_node, 8, action_name
        proc add_child with action_node, col_def
        proc add_child with alter_node, action_node

    Otherwise If is_drop is equal to 1:
        proc advance_token with parser

        Note: Expect COLUMN keyword (optional)
        Set is_column to proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_COLUMN from Lexer
        If is_column is equal to 1:
            proc advance_token with parser
        End If

        Set col_name to proc parse_primary_expression with parser

        Set action_node to proc create_sql_node with SQL_IDENTIFIER, 0, 0, line, column
        Set action_name to "DROP"
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with action_node, 8, action_name
        proc add_child with action_node, col_name
        proc add_child with alter_node, action_node
    End If

    Return alter_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
DROP TABLE / DROP INDEX share the same shape; the object kind is
stored in the SQL_DROP node's metadata slot rather than as a child
node so downstream code can switch on a single integer.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Builds a SQL_DROP node at the DROP position. After consuming DROP,
checks for TABLE (sets object_type=1) or INDEX (sets object_type=2);
unrecognised follow-up leaves object_type=0. Stores object_type at
the metadata offset (24). Parses the object name as a primary
expression and attaches it as the only child.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_drop" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse DROP statement
    Note: Format: DROP TABLE/INDEX name

    Let token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 32

    Let drop_node be proc create_sql_node with SQL_DROP, 0, 0, line, column

    proc advance_token with parser  Note: Consume DROP

    Note: Parse object type (TABLE or INDEX)
    Let is_table be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_TABLE from Lexer
    Let is_index be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_INDEX from Lexer

    Let object_type be 0
    If is_table is equal to 1:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Set object_type to 1  Note: 1 = TABLE
    Otherwise If is_index is equal to 1:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Set object_type to 2  Note: 2 = INDEX
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with drop_node, 24, object_type  Note: Store type in metadata

    Note: Parse object name
    Let object_name be proc parse_table_name with parser

    If object_name is not equal to 0:
        proc add_child with drop_node, object_name
    End If

    Return drop_node
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Top-Level Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Public entry point: takes a raw source string, owns the lexer/parser
lifecycle internally, and returns the parsed AST. Statement type is
selected from the leading keyword (SELECT/INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE/CREATE/
ALTER/DROP) and dispatched to the right parse_* helper.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Creates a SQL lexer; bails with 0 on failure. Wraps it in a parser;
on failure destroys the lexer and bails. Reads current token type and
dispatches via a chain of Otherwise If branches into parse_select /
parse_insert / parse_update / parse_delete / parse_create_table /
parse_alter_table / parse_drop. Any unrecognised leading token leaves
ast at 0. The function returns the AST handle without destroying
parser/lexer — that becomes the caller's responsibility once they have
extracted what they need.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
source is untrusted SQL text; the parser tolerates malformed inputs by
returning partial ASTs and recording errors in the parser, never
crashing on unexpected tokens.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "parse_sql" takes source as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse SQL source into AST

    Note: Create lexer
    Let lexer be proc create_sql_lexer from Lexer with source

    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Create parser
    Let parser be proc create_sql_parser with lexer

    If parser is equal to 0:
        proc destroy_sql_lexer from Lexer with lexer
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Determine statement type and parse
    Let token_type be proc current_token_type with parser

    Let ast be 0

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_SELECT from Lexer:
        Set ast to proc parse_select with parser
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to TOKEN_INSERT from Lexer:
        Set ast to proc parse_insert with parser
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to TOKEN_UPDATE from Lexer:
        Set ast to proc parse_update with parser
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to TOKEN_DELETE from Lexer:
        Set ast to proc parse_delete with parser
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to TOKEN_CREATE from Lexer:
        Set ast to proc parse_create_table with parser
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to TOKEN_ALTER from Lexer:
        Set ast to proc parse_alter_table with parser
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to TOKEN_DROP from Lexer:
        Set ast to proc parse_drop with parser
    End If

    Note: Cleanup
    proc destroy_sql_parser with parser
    proc destroy_sql_lexer from Lexer with lexer

    Return ast
End Process

Note: End of SQL Parser
